Description: Rectangular pendant or tag of dark green stone, perforated at the top, with a design scored on one side of several illegible signs encircled within a probable imitation of a cartouche.
Curator's comments: "The piece of a whetstone is noticeable, as it appears to bear an attempt at a cartouche by some one who knew nothing of hieroglyphs, nor indeed of any writing apparently" (W.M.F. Petrie, Tanis ii, Nebesheh and Defenneh, p. 72 § 68, pl. xxiv, 5).
Bibliographic references: Petrie 1888 / Tanis. Part II. Nebesheh (Am) and Defenneh (Tahpanhes) (p. 72 § 68, pl. xxiv, 5)
Leclère and Spencer 2014 / Tell Dafana Reconsidered: The Archaeology of an Egyptian Frontier Town (p.86, p.187, pl.29)
